Inasmuch as, if we omit from consideration the clement of duration in time, sounds differ from one another in three most prominent particulare,l their loudness (force, intensity), their timbre (quality, Kana-Forte), and their pitch, any one of these qualities or properties may be described as that particular in which asound varies, if the other two are kept constant. If, then, the notes of one and the same instru- ment are sounded with the same degree of loudness, the notes will differ only in their pitch. Although Helmholtz's dis- covery that ordinary musical notes are oomposed of a number of related pitches, of which one is predomineut, is now uni- versally accepted, and although timbre is thus reduced toa matter of pitchos, the threefold division of the characteres musical sounds is still useful. By the pitch of a note, then, the predominant pitch is generally meant, and since there is uo indication that timbre was analyzed in this way by any of the ancients, we shall not have to do with any but this, the nominal pitch of a musical sound.

But it is by no means certain that the existence of the vibra- tione by which sound is produced was unknown to the Greeks.
